raditions. Therefore, to understand the Malleus, one must also understand the contemporary and subsequent debates over the reality and nature of witches. This book argues that although the Malleus was a highly idiosyncratic text, its arguments were powerfully compelling and therefore remained influential long after alternatives were forgotten. Consequently, although focused on a single text, this study has important implications for fifteenth-century witchcraft theory.This is a fascinating work on the Malleus Maleficarum and will be essential to students and academics of late medieval and early modern history, religion and witchcraft studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWitchcraftxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aDominican inquisitor.  aHeinrich Institoris.  aMalleus Maleficarum.  aMontague Summers.  alate medieval text.  aofficial complacency.  aspiritual threat.  atreatises.  awitchcraft.  awitches.1 aBroedel, Hans Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526137814zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526137814zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526137814/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA